# Firebase/Firestore Database Standards

## Scope of This Rule

**This rule covers**: Firebase/Firestore **implementation** - setup, offline persistence, real-time sync, queries, security patterns.

**For generic database design principles** (schema structure, indexes, best practices), see **Rule 23** (database-rules.mdc).

**For local SQLite**, see **Rule 05** (database-sqlite.mdc).

---

## TL;DR - Quick Reference

**Offline-first setup**:
```typescript
// Enable offline persistence
await enableIndexedDbPersistence(firestore);
```

**UUID-based IDs**:
```typescript
// Generate offline-friendly IDs
const docId = uuid(); // Client-generated
await setDoc(doc(db, 'users', docId), userData);
```

**Realtime listeners**:
```typescript
// Auto-sync when online
onSnapshot(query, (snapshot) => {
  // Handle updates
});
```

**Key patterns**:
- Use UUIDs for document IDs (offline-first)
- Enable offline persistence
- Use subcollections for nested data
- Batch writes for multi-document updates
- Plan for "last write wins" conflicts

**Read full rule for**: Complete setup, query patterns, security, best practices.

---

## Why Firestore for Offline-First?

### Firestore Strengths

✅ **Built-in offline support** - Local cache handles reads/writes  
✅ **Automatic sync** - Queues writes, syncs when online  
✅ **Real-time updates** - Other devices get changes automatically  
✅ **Managed infrastructure** - No server to maintain  
✅ **Scalable** - Handles growth without re-architecture

### When to Use Firestore vs SQLite

| Use Case | Recommendation |
|----------|----------------|
| **Multi-device sync** | Firestore |
| **Offline-only, no sync** | SQLite |
| **Complex relational queries** | SQLite (or use Firestore + local denormalization) |
| **Real-time collaboration** | Firestore |
| **Cost-sensitive at scale** | SQLite + custom sync (more work) |

