## Data Structure Patterns

### Collections vs Subcollections

```typescript
// Pattern 1: Top-level collections
// Good for: Independent entities, cross-household queries
users/{userId}
households/{householdId}
transactions/{transactionId}

// Pattern 2: Subcollections
// Good for: Nested data, scoped queries, automatic cleanup
households/{householdId}/budgets/{budgetId}
households/{householdId}/budgets/{budgetId}/categories/{categoryId}
transactions/{transactionId}/receipts/{receiptId}
```

### When to Use Each

```typescript
// ✅ Subcollections: When data belongs to parent
households/{householdId}/members/{userId}
households/{householdId}/transactions/{txId}

// ✅ Top-level: When data is referenced across parents
users/{userId} // Used by multiple households
categories/{categoryId} // Shared templates

// ❌ Don't deeply nest (>3 levels)
// Bad: a/b/c/d/e/f - queries become complex
```

### Document Structure

```typescript
// src/infrastructure/firebase/models.ts

// ✅ GOOD: Flat structure
interface UserDocument {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  name: string;
  household_ids: string[]; // Array of references
  created_at: Timestamp;
  updated_at: Timestamp;
}

// ❌ BAD: Nested objects (hard to query)
interface UserDocumentBad {
  id: string;
  profile: {
    personal: {
      name: string;
      age: number;
    };
    contact: {
      email: string;
      phone: string;
    };
  };
}

// ✅ Use subcollections for nested data instead
users/{userId}/preferences/{key}
```

